#. Tag: glossterm
#: glossary.docbook:8
#, no-c-format
msgid "degrees"
msgstr "ibigero"

#. Tag: para
#: glossary.docbook:9
#, fuzzy, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Degrees are units to measure angles or turns. A full turn is 360 degrees, a "
"half turn 180 degrees and a quarter turn 90 degrees. The commands "
"<userinput>turnleft</userinput>, <userinput>turnright</userinput> and "
"<userinput>direction</userinput> need an input in degrees."
msgstr ""
"Kuri Cyangwa . A Cyuzuye ni Dogere , A Dogere na A Dogere . Amabwiriza "
"<userinput> </userinput> , <userinput> </userinput> na <userinput> "
"Icyerekezo </userinput> Iyinjiza in Dogere . "

#. Tag: glossterm
#: glossary.docbook:13
#, fuzzy, no-c-format
msgid "input and output of commands"
msgstr "Iyinjiza na Ibisohoka Bya Amabwiriza "

#. Tag: para
#: glossary.docbook:14
#, fuzzy, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Some commands take input, some commands give output, some commands take "
"input <emphasis>and</emphasis> give output and some commands neither take "
"input nor give output."
msgstr ""
"Amabwiriza Iyinjiza , Amabwiriza Ibisohoka , Amabwiriza Iyinjiza <emphasis> "
"na </emphasis> Ibisohoka na Amabwiriza Iyinjiza Ibisohoka . "

#. Tag: para
#: glossary.docbook:15
#, fuzzy, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Some examples of commands that only take input are: <screen>\n"
"forward 50\n"
"pencolor 255,0,0\n"
"print \"Hello!\"\n"
"</screen> The <userinput>forward</userinput> command takes <userinput>50</"
"userinput> as input. <userinput>forward</userinput> needs this input to know "
"how many <glossterm linkend=\"pixels\">pixels</glossterm> it should go "
"forward. <userinput>pencolor</userinput> takes a color as input and "
"<userinput>print</userinput> takes a string (a piece of text) as input. "
"Please note that the input can also be a container. The next example "
"illustrates this:"
msgstr ""
"Ingero Bya Amabwiriza Iyinjiza : <screen> \n"
"Imbere , 0 %S , \" ! \" \n"
"</screen> <userinput> Imbere </userinput> command <userinput> 50% </"
"userinput> Nka Iyinjiza . <userinput> Imbere </userinput> iyi Iyinjiza Kuri "
"< = \" pigiseli \" > pigiseli < /> Gyayo Imbere . <userinput> </userinput> A "
"Ibara: Nka Iyinjiza na <userinput> &Shyira ku rupapuro... </userinput> A "
"Ikurikiranyanyuguti ( A Bya Umwandiko ) Nka Iyinjiza . Impugukirwa i "
"Iyinjiza A . Ibikurikira > Urugero: iyi : "

#. Tag: screen
#: glossary.docbook:18
#, fuzzy, no-c-format
msgid ""
"$x = 50\n"
"print $x\n"
"forward 50\n"
"$str = \"hello!\"\n"
"print $str"
msgstr ""
"x = = \" Muraho ! \" \n"
"&Shyira ku rupapuro... "

#. Tag: para
#: glossary.docbook:20
#, fuzzy, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Now some examples of commands that give output: <screen>\n"
"$x = ask \"Please type something and press OK... thanks!\"\n"
"$r = random 1,100\n"
"</screen> The <userinput>ask</userinput> command takes a string as input, "
"and outputs the number or string that is entered. As you can see, the output "
"of <userinput>ask</userinput> is stored in the container <userinput>x</"
"userinput>. The <userinput>random</userinput> command also gives output. In "
"this case it outputs a number between 1 and 100. The output of the random is "
"again stored in a container, named <userinput>r</userinput>. Note that the "
"containers <userinput>x</userinput> and <userinput>r</userinput> are not "
"used in the example code above."
msgstr ""
"Ingero Bya Amabwiriza Ibisohoka : <screen> \n"
"x = \" Ubwoko: na Kanda ... ! \" \n"
"r = Bitunguranye 1 , </screen> <userinput> </userinput> command A "
"Ikurikiranyanyuguti Nka Iyinjiza , na i Umubare Cyangwa Ikurikiranyanyuguti "
"ni . , i Ibisohoka Bya <userinput> </userinput> ni in i <userinput> x </"
"userinput> . <userinput> Bitunguranye </userinput> command Ibisohoka . iyi A "
"Umubare hagati 1 na 100 . Ibisohoka Bya i Bitunguranye ni Nanone in A , "
"&Cyitwa: <userinput> r </userinput> . icyitonderwa i <userinput> x </"
"userinput> na <userinput> r </userinput> OYA Byakoreshejwe in i Urugero: "
"Inyandikoporogaramu hejuru . "

